<section id="intro" class="chapter">
    <h2>1. Introduction: Engines Behind Blitzkrieg</h2>
    <p>
        German drivers were the backbone of mobile warfare. Their trucks moved fuel, ammunition, rations, and  
        staff officers across rapidly shifting fronts. But shortages, harsh winters, and constant enemy attacks  
        turned logistics into a continuous struggle.
    </p>
    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d1/Opel_Blitz_3.6-36S.jpg" alt="Opel Blitz">
        <p><em>The Opel Blitz — symbol of Wehrmacht mobility.</em></p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="vehicles" class="chapter">
    <h2>2. Vehicles of the Wehrmacht</h2>

    <h3>Opel Blitz</h3>
    <p>The most common German truck; versatile, reliable, and used on all fronts.</p>

    <h3>Mercedes-Benz L3000</h3>
    <p>Heavy-duty truck especially valued in North Africa.</p>

    <h3>Captured Foreign Trucks</h3>
    <p>
        Germany relied heavily on French, Czech, Soviet, and Italian trucks. Spare-part shortages  
        caused improvised fixes and mismatched convoys.
    </p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f9/Mercedes_L3000_SdKfz.jpg" alt="Mercedes Truck">
    </div>
</section>

<section id="routes" class="chapter">
    <h2>3. Operational Routes & Challenges</h2>

    <h3>Eastern Front</h3>
    <p>Winter froze engines solid; summer mud immobilized entire divisions.</p>

    <h3>Afrika Korps</h3>
    <p>Drivers fought sand, heat, dust-clogged carburetors, and endless fuel shortages.</p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4b/Deutsches_Afrikakorps_sands.jpg" alt="Afrikakorps">
    </div>

    <h3>Western Europe</h3>
    <p>Air power forced night driving and heavy camouflage during daylight.</p>
</section>

<section id="safety" class="chapter">
    <h2>4. Safety Regulations & Camouflage</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Lights dimmed or blue-filtered</strong> to avoid Allied aircraft.</li>
        <li><strong>Camouflage tarps</strong> required during all daytime stops.</li>
        <li><strong>Convoy spacing:</strong> minimum 60 meters under strafing threat.</li>
        <li><strong>Fuel discipline:</strong> no idling; every liter counted.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="maintenance" class="chapter">
    <h2>5. Field Maintenance & Shortage Solutions</h2>

    <h3>Critical Tools</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Hand pump for fuel barrels</li>
        <li>Spare distributor points</li>
        <li>Soldering set</li>
        <li>Mixed spanner sizes (due to foreign vehicles)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Improvised Repairs</h3>
    <p><strong>Radiator leaks:</strong> Patch with ground coffee + sealant.</p>
    <p><strong>Sand in carburetors:</strong> Clean with kerosene and cloth filters.</p>
    <p><strong>Snowbound engines:</strong> Light fires under oil pans (dangerous but common).</p>
</section>

<section id="life" class="chapter">
    <h2>6. Life in the Motor Column</h2>
    <p>
        Drivers endured freezing nights, dust storms, partisans, and constant aircraft attacks.  
        Many lived out of their cabs and carried personal kits including coffee, bread, and  
        makeshift stoves.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
        “The infantry wins battles — the trucks win campaigns.”
    </blockquote>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8d/WWII_German_Truck_Column.jpg" alt="Truck column">
    </div>
</section>

